The Indian Ocean's dazzling  coral and dense mangroves suffered a beating during the tsunami, but  environmentalists say they also protected the coastline and saved  lives by absorbing some of the waves' power.
As the people of  Indonesia's Aceh province try to rebuild lives shattered by the  tsunami disaster, officials are also assessing the environmental  damage to the coast which bore the brunt of the giant waves.
A major conference of biologists and  policymakers got under way in Paris on Monday to calls for the world  to draw the environmental lessons from Asia's December 26 tsunami  disaster.
